<div class=3D"post-body entry-content float-container" id=3D"post-body-8343=
198307486879624">
<span style=3D"font-family: inherit;">Setting up WinDbg for kernel-mode deb=
ugging is a fairly trivial process, however, it's easy to miss (or incorrec=
tly configure) a step causing you to waste precious time.&nbsp;</span><br>
<span style=3D"font-family: inherit;"><br></span>
<span style=3D"font-family: inherit;">In this post, I have written a tutori=
al that goes through the entire process of setting up WinDbg (and configuri=
ng symbol lookup) for kernel-mode debugging with VMware <b>using a named pi=
pe and a virtual serial connection</b>.&nbsp;</span><br>
<span style=3D"font-family: inherit;"></span><br>
<a name=3D"more"></a><span style=3D"font-family: inherit;">Serial port debu=
gging was chosen for compatibility reasons. Other debugging modes like ethe=
rnet/network, while quicker, require special hardware (e.g. certain network=
 interface cards are compatible and many are not) and are only supported on=
 newer versions of Windows.&nbsp;</span><br>
<h2>
<span style=3D"font-family: inherit;">Requirements</span></h2>
<div>
<ul>
<li>A copy of either <a href=3D"https://www.vmware.com/products/workstation=
/workstation-evaluation.html" target=3D"_blank">VMware Workstation</a> (fre=
e 30-day trial) or <a href=3D"https://www.vmware.com/products/player/player=
pro-evaluation.html" target=3D"_blank">VMware Player</a> (entirely free for=
 non-commercial use) for Windows. I'll be using <b>VMware Workstation 12.5.=
7 (build-5813279)</b>.</li>
<li>A Windows operating system installed on your host and guest (VM). These=
 do not have to be the same versions of Windows, but should be running at l=
east Windows XP or later. My host and guest OS are both running <b>Windows =
x64 10.0.15063 (Version 1703)</b>.</li>
<ul>
<li>A free copy of Windows 10 can be found <a href=3D"https://www.microsoft=
.com/en-us/software-download/windows10" target=3D"_blank">here</a> as long =
as the tool is run on a machine that has a valid Windows license (of any ve=
rsion). Follow the steps to create an ISO file. Use the ISO file to install=
 the OS on the Virtual Machine (helpful documentation can be found on the <=
a href=3D"https://kb.vmware.com/selfservice/microsites/search.do?language=
=3Den_US&amp;cmd=3DdisplayKC&amp;externalId=3D2128790" target=3D"_blank">VM=
ware website</a> and <a href=3D"http://www.wikihow.com/Install-Windows-7-on=
-a-VMware-Workstation" target=3D"_blank">WikiHow</a>).</li>
</ul>
<li>WinDbg.</li>
<ul>
<li>The latest and greatest version can be downloaded from this <a href=3D"=
https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/hardware/download-windbg" tar=
get=3D"_blank">page</a> (direct <a href=3D"https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/=
p/?LinkId=3D845298" target=3D"_blank">link</a>). This requires installation=
 through the Windows SDK, however, you can unselect all components except "=
<i>Debugging Tools for Windows</i>" if you do not plan on doing any softwar=
e development. I'll be using <b>WinDbg x64 10.0.15063.400</b>.</li>
</ul>
</ul>
</div>
<h2>
Setting up symbols on your host</h2>
<div>
<div>
Microsoft provides <a href=3D"https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/build/re=
ference/pdbstripped-strip-private-symbols" target=3D"_blank">stripped</a> (=
"redacted") PDBs (commonly referred to as "symbols") for most of their soft=
ware releases. This includes the kernel components that power the operating=
 system. In order to leverage this very useful information, we'll need to s=
etup WinDbg so it can access these resources.&nbsp;</div>
</div>
<div>
<ol>
<li>Locate your WinDbg installation.</li>
<ul>
<li>For most people, this will be located in the following directory:<br><s=
pan style=3D"font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , m=
onospace;">C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\Debuggers\x64</span></li>
</ul>
<li><span style=3D"font-family: inherit;">Right-click on the </span><span s=
tyle=3D"font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monosp=
ace;">windbg.exe</span><span style=3D"font-family: inherit;"> file and sele=
ct "Create shortcut". This shortcut should be placed on the desktop or anot=
her convenient place.</span></li>
<li>Right-click on the shortcut that you just created. Select "Properties".=
 In the "Shortcut" tab, you'll see a window similar to this:
<center>
<a href=3D"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/7rfCVBhamYQGSH8FJNF-SSoj75Hbz3=
p68z8lo6eaZQdO-bqYXAb7GAHXMyS2X544bBaO0sPyOIcD5UMV0qa3KTW5GTG2r8nolU2A-hP7x=
KNd5jSfIAoXuCspftkMP9eXXgPDQWJP" target=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"320" src=
=3D"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/7rfCVBhamYQGSH8FJNF-SSoj75Hbz3p68z8lo=
6eaZQdO-bqYXAb7GAHXMyS2X544bBaO0sPyOIcD5UMV0qa3KTW5GTG2r8nolU2A-hP7xKNd5jSf=
IAoXuCspftkMP9eXXgPDQWJP" style=3D"border: none; font-family: arial; font-s=
ize: 14.6667px; text-align: center; transform: rotate(0rad); white-space: p=
re-wrap;" width=3D"228"></a></center>
</li>
<li>Select the "Target:" text field and append a string of the following fo=
rmat:<br><span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;couri=
er new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">-y "srv*c:\symbols*https:/=
/msdl.microsoft.com/download/symbols"</span><br>
</li>
<ul>
<li>The syntax of this command string is:<br>
<span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&qu=
ot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">srv*[local cache]*[private symbol s=
erver]*https://msdl.microsoft.com/download/symbols</span>
</li>
<li>
This will download all available symbols, as necessary, from the Microsoft =
Symbol Server to your local symbol directory at <span style=3D"font-family:=
 &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">c:\symbols</sp=
an>. If you prefer to place your downloaded symbols somewhere else, choose =
another local path instead.
</li>
<li>
This command supports multiple symbol servers. For example, if you wish to =
pull symbols from a remote share, you can append to this path, e.g:
<br>
<span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&qu=
ot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">srv*c:\symbols*\\mainserver\symbols=
*https://msdl.microsoft.com/download/symbols</span>
</li>
<li>
Example of a fully qualified "Target:" text field:
<br>
<span style=3D"font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; ,=
 monospace;">"C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\Debuggers\x64\windbg.e=
xe" </span><span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;cou=
rier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">-y "srv*c:\symbols*https=
://msdl.microsoft.com/download/symbols"</span></li>
</ul>
<li>Save your shortcut changes by pushing 'OK'. Now that we've instructed W=
inDbg to pull symbol information from the Microsoft Symbol Server, let's te=
st it to ensure that everything is working.</li>
<ul>
<li>
We pass the symbol path via a command line parameter to WinDbg for reliabil=
ity reasons. We could have, alternatively, configured an environment variab=
le, <a href=3D"https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ee4=
16588(v=3Dvs.85).aspx" target=3D"_blank">_NT_SYMBOL_PATH</a>, to achieve th=
e same functionality, but it's a less elegant solution.</li>
</ul>
<li>Run the shortcut and a copy of the pre-installed application Notepad.</=
li>
<li>Select "File" then "Attach to a Process..." (or hit F6) in WinDbg. Scro=
ll down all the way and select "notepad.exe" from your process list. Then h=
it 'OK'.<br><div style=3D"text-align: center;">
<a href=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/Tr1mTZk0sXL8CwmFQRJIEtr72wn9dW=
J3tODca-vcKogjfbpr68IHtU1wAEvmFLwMbaOALUqeFbY04rytSOmY9fap3ki5uFAxzzUImLFKi=
Ap6paNZizdjEW1qwLZSbeqaZXoVfs7Z" target=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"361" src=
=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/Tr1mTZk0sXL8CwmFQRJIEtr72wn9dWJ3tODca=
-vcKogjfbpr68IHtU1wAEvmFLwMbaOALUqeFbY04rytSOmY9fap3ki5uFAxzzUImLFKiAp6paNZ=
izdjEW1qwLZSbeqaZXoVfs7Z" style=3D"border: none; font-family: Arial; font-s=
ize: 11pt; transform: rotate(0rad); white-space: pre-wrap;" width=3D"257"><=
/a></div>
</li>
<li>A "Command" window will appear. We'll use this to issue commands to Win=
Dbg.</li>
<ul>
<li>
I like to expand my "Command" window so it takes up the full view in the de=
bugger. You can do this by right clicking on the "Command" window title and=
 selecting "Dock":
<br><div style=3D"text-align: center;">
<a href=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/7j-fVyPD-XkFfRbalJ4Grz837alwTq=
AemraNC7gVKh0dFtoH1qjc_VgTlxw2fF-VhywahZSnbnho_qZAT3idHGChML-WtpPV4evRbCMhq=
qtdtwmdftB-apFn9mEkCImEu3ViVZJl" target=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"400" src=
=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/7j-fVyPD-XkFfRbalJ4Grz837alwTqAemraNC=
7gVKh0dFtoH1qjc_VgTlxw2fF-VhywahZSnbnho_qZAT3idHGChML-WtpPV4evRbCMhqqtdtwmd=
ftB-apFn9mEkCImEu3ViVZJl" style=3D"border: none; transform: rotate(0rad);" =
width=3D"640"></a></div>
</li>
</ul>
<li>Let's try to load symbols for all the running modules (executable and D=
LLs). First, let's list what modules are currently loaded in our process by=
 using the <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;cou=
rier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">lm</span> (<b>l</b>ist <=
b>m</b>odules) command in the text box immediately to the right of "&gt;". =
This is in the bottom left corner of the "Command" window:<br><div style=3D=
"text-align: center;">
<a href=3D"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/vER6IpiNr8MkYuShFnwR9h2mqfxvlA=
E5hmfzZmaG-oZpKSbjMi5m-mafNetG80lyUtx0OFM5EvibDFOJttOM5DEtAyRLuhoztpV3QYLuF=
vUIDRvMvb5ZEp4oK74kCZBKJnzMJc8d" target=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"417" src=
=3D"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/vER6IpiNr8MkYuShFnwR9h2mqfxvlAE5hmfzZ=
maG-oZpKSbjMi5m-mafNetG80lyUtx0OFM5EvibDFOJttOM5DEtAyRLuhoztpV3QYLuFvUIDRvM=
vb5ZEp4oK74kCZBKJnzMJc8d" style=3D"border: none; font-family: arial; font-s=
ize: 11pt; transform: rotate(0rad); white-space: pre-wrap;" width=3D"640"><=
/a></div>
If your list looks different from mine, don't worry. Different versions of =
Windows and different versions of Notepad will have different modules loade=
d.</li>
<li>Next, let's force a symbol load of all modules within our process by ex=
ecuting <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courie=
r new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">.reload /f</span>:
<ul>
<li><b>Pro-tip</b>: WinDbg has a great manual. To access it, you can type t=
he command <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;cou=
rier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">.hh</span> within the de=
bugger (or select "Help" and then "Search" from the menu bar). Typing <span=
 style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; ,=
 &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">.hh search terms go here</span> automati=
cally runs a search for the user supplied argument. </li>
<li><span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier ne=
w&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">.hh .reload</span> documents th=
e .reload command. In particular, it explains why the /f argument is suppli=
ed.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
It may take WinDbg a few moments to load all symbol information. You can se=
e the status of WinDbg in the bottom left corner (next to where commands ar=
e inserted). After WinDbg has loaded symbols, run the <span style=3D"backgr=
ound-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&q=
uot; , monospace;">lm</span> command again.=20
</li>
<ul>
<li><b>
Pro-tip</b>: If WinDbg stays "BUSY" for a long time, you can force it to st=
op its current task by pushing Ctrl+Break on your keyboard or by selecting =
"Debug" and then "Break" from the menu bar.
<br><div style=3D"text-align: center;">
<a href=3D"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/Fh2uGYoubVqzDEh8RS8cmsJQXU8vGH=
blJlRWlDCQEN3yh3lViya3krNk15OT0IuN7uRKCvpYJ9YWQIzVDrYpXFZ15VbiYzleIQ46SIj3C=
7E9-MEvccwU4EE2_mM2Sk1Y2Ygx7bfq" target=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"408" src=
=3D"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/Fh2uGYoubVqzDEh8RS8cmsJQXU8vGHblJlRWl=
DCQEN3yh3lViya3krNk15OT0IuN7uRKCvpYJ9YWQIzVDrYpXFZ15VbiYzleIQ46SIj3C7E9-MEv=
ccwU4EE2_mM2Sk1Y2Ygx7bfq" style=3D"border: none; transform: rotate(0rad);" =
width=3D"624"></a></div>
As you can see, most modules now have a local symbol path listed to the rig=
ht of their <b>module name</b>. It's very possible that there may be some m=
odules that still do not have symbols loaded. These modules are most likely=
 not distributed by Microsoft (e.g. 3rd party antivirus vendors).=20
</li>
</ul>
<li>For validation, go to the directory that you've setup for your local sy=
mbol cache, e.g. <span style=3D"font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quo=
t;courier&quot; , monospace;">C:\symbols</span>. If the folder contains dat=
a, you're set and can skip the troubleshooting step.</li>
</ol>
<h3>
Troubleshooting</h3>
</div>
<h4>
Verbose output</h4>
<div>
The easiest way to troubleshoot problems with symbol loading is to enable v=
erbose output with the <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-famil=
y: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">!sym noisy</=
span> command:<br>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">
<span style=3D"font-family: &quot;arial&quot;; font-size: 11pt; vertical-al=
ign: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"><a href=3D"https://lh3.googleusercon=
tent.com/YSKSpC6eIg-W5T8F3cBOFRDFSj9r_yqzOjcCbgCCeRUB-vHQxstRH7zBPfhduq_xZA=
htK29FmK_fxgHKdnAGIQOwTJNzL_bWXMl2q6Ttv4H0g0KF7BaXwpI5EYR1KFTJaLh49Yoa" tar=
get=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"339" src=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com=
/YSKSpC6eIg-W5T8F3cBOFRDFSj9r_yqzOjcCbgCCeRUB-vHQxstRH7zBPfhduq_xZAhtK29FmK=
_fxgHKdnAGIQOwTJNzL_bWXMl2q6Ttv4H0g0KF7BaXwpI5EYR1KFTJaLh49Yoa" style=3D"bo=
rder: none; transform: rotate(0rad);" width=3D"624"></a></span><br>
<div style=3D"text-align: left;">
Next, issue the <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quo=
t;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">.reload /f</span> c=
ommand.<br>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">
<span style=3D"font-family: &quot;arial&quot;; font-size: 11pt; vertical-al=
ign: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"><a href=3D"https://lh4.googleusercon=
tent.com/fH3ip474LJ_rJvRa-f54dY8wEgASEC6cRDbuZncGvLRXOVpnbuALhLBvY7IjGL-vwF=
6E1EzTK3vz23vN4aiWE3NK3Cwa4RShcIFscX8g_WeIUXOe5KRAoZ-bDhge3Vp6QdHJwpCy" tar=
get=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"339" src=3D"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com=
/fH3ip474LJ_rJvRa-f54dY8wEgASEC6cRDbuZncGvLRXOVpnbuALhLBvY7IjGL-vwF6E1EzTK3=
vz23vN4aiWE3NK3Cwa4RShcIFscX8g_WeIUXOe5KRAoZ-bDhge3Vp6QdHJwpCy" style=3D"bo=
rder: none; transform: rotate(0rad);" width=3D"624"></a></span><br>
<div style=3D"text-align: left;">
In my example, it's easy to see that I mistyped the URL to the Microsoft Sy=
mbol Server in my shortcut's "Target:" field. After applying the right URL =
to my "Target:" field, I can restart WinDbg and try again.&nbsp;</div>
</div>
</div>
<div style=3D"text-align: left;">
<h4>
The lazy fix</h4>
<div>
<div>
WinDbg may be able to fix the problem for you automagically if you issue <s=
pan style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot=
; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">.symfix</span> and then <span style=
=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot=
;courier&quot; , monospace;">.reload /f</span>. In this case, WinDbg will a=
lter your symbol path to the Microsoft Symbol Server. Your downloaded symbo=
ls will be stored, locally, in WinDbg's current working directory (<span st=
yle=3D"font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospa=
ce;">C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\Debuggers\x64</span>) or <span =
style=3D"font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monos=
pace;">C:\ProgramData\dbg</span>.<br>
<h2>
Setting up VMware on your host</h2>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<ol>
<li>Select the VM you wish to enable kernel-mode debugging on within VMware=
.
<ul>
<li>VMs should be listed in the "Library" pane on the left of the GUI. If t=
he "Library" pane is missing, you can restore it by selecting "View" then "=
Customize" and choosing "Library" (or hit F9).</li>
<li>If your VM is not listed in the "Library" pane, you can manually naviga=
te to it's .vmx file via "File" and then "Open..." (or Control+O).</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Ensure that the VM is currently not running. If it's currently active, =
power it off via the menu bar: "VM" then "Power" then "Shut Down Guest" (or=
 Ctrl+E).</li>
<li>Select "Edit virtual machine settings". Ensure that you are on the "Har=
dware" tab. </li>
<li>Select the "Add" button and choose "Serial Port" from the "Add Hardware=
 Wizard". Hit "Next &gt;".<br><div style=3D"text-align: center;">
<a href=3D"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/p4XSQu9YUKjpZSR_nQwoBLXkLmAxog=
hNSohycDfIvEiZtqEAfT_TQfZz9t1AAMOZzdq5EeOklHIHqJTFLGcLLjcOWOUx4NrPCutkPrSlM=
sI3U4l3k90pA4Y-FaGR7UnV59gU08I7" target=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"449" src=
=3D"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/p4XSQu9YUKjpZSR_nQwoBLXkLmAxoghNSohyc=
DfIvEiZtqEAfT_TQfZz9t1AAMOZzdq5EeOklHIHqJTFLGcLLjcOWOUx4NrPCutkPrSlMsI3U4l3=
k90pA4Y-FaGR7UnV59gU08I7" style=3D"border: none; font-family: Arial; font-s=
ize: 11pt; transform: rotate(0rad); white-space: pre-wrap;" width=3D"624"><=
/a></div>
</li>
<li>Ensure that the "Serial port" checkbox is targeting "Output to named pi=
pe" and then hit "Next &gt;".<br><div style=3D"text-align: center;">
<a href=3D"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-nHXy8jcVNmKTdaLqL8eYO8a9iwGqt=
VORtYar5XclQCM_8IHie89iH0x9zoqbvqT61NK3kS99VbjMe_o01KuWWZipBgid5Au6Hw56sG8m=
s5MpZD3fvT8ryrEtgsqB8xmWtBR5SoV" target=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"385" src=
=3D"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-nHXy8jcVNmKTdaLqL8eYO8a9iwGqtVORtYar=
5XclQCM_8IHie89iH0x9zoqbvqT61NK3kS99VbjMe_o01KuWWZipBgid5Au6Hw56sG8ms5MpZD3=
fvT8ryrEtgsqB8xmWtBR5SoV" style=3D"border: none; transform: rotate(0rad);" =
width=3D"442"></a></div>
</li>
<li>On the final screen, you should see similar settings to this. Make a no=
te of the "Named pipe" field and then hit "Finish".<br><div style=3D"text-a=
lign: center;">
<a href=3D"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/toLwL-HBt_k5nSEuJWhrA_71dGdRQo=
oJp9gZJ5lIf9zn0eosorKBhgXmv7NdjEPuie8472YogSFqeGncmSWf7LnS1E2pMKa-QcFdc7do0=
qM4UvYmspZCGydIMZgBr2Oxw3KorUKl" target=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"385" src=
=3D"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/toLwL-HBt_k5nSEuJWhrA_71dGdRQooJp9gZJ=
5lIf9zn0eosorKBhgXmv7NdjEPuie8472YogSFqeGncmSWf7LnS1E2pMKa-QcFdc7do0qM4UvYm=
spZCGydIMZgBr2Oxw3KorUKl" style=3D"border: none; font-family: Arial; font-s=
ize: 11pt; transform: rotate(0rad); white-space: pre-wrap;" width=3D"442"><=
/a></div>
<ul>
<li>
Ensure that your settings match those above. In particular, output to a "Na=
med pipe" at <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;c=
ourier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">\\.\pipe\com_1</span> =
and ensure that the first drop down box has "This end is the server" select=
ed and the last drop down box has "The other end is a virtual machine" sele=
cted. Finally, make sure that you've selected "Connect at power on".
</li>
<li>
The <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier ne=
w&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">com_1</span> substring can be c=
hanged to something else (e.g. <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee;"><=
span style=3D"font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , =
monospace;">kdebug</span></span>), but it needs to be remembered and the ex=
act name should be used within WinDbg too.
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>The "Add Hardware Wizard" will now close and a new "Serial port" will b=
e added to your "Hardware" tab. Ensure the "Yield CPU on poll" checkbox is =
selected in "Virtual Machine Settings". <b>Make a note of the number to the=
 right of "Serial Port" (if there is no number, it's assumed to be 1)</b>.<=
span style=3D"font-family: &quot;arial&quot;; font-size: 11pt; vertical-ali=
gn: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"><br><div style=3D"text-align: center;=
">
<a href=3D"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/TH3CnVacZcnioalLQqOMEOZQlu854p=
epj9EYsZBMidhs8N2p5xr4jIwF_dlA6wl2wXmedE7pwCnq4cdwakAQ-0zfhguYRGbujvJ0mRezW=
-UfQKLFJX1O63FT7I49bZd7Mz-oZWDs" style=3D"font-size: 11pt;" target=3D"_blan=
k"><img height=3D"572" src=3D"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/TH3CnVacZcn=
ioalLQqOMEOZQlu854pepj9EYsZBMidhs8N2p5xr4jIwF_dlA6wl2wXmedE7pwCnq4cdwakAQ-0=
zfhguYRGbujvJ0mRezW-UfQKLFJX1O63FT7I49bZd7Mz-oZWDs" style=3D"border: none; =
transform: rotate(0rad);" width=3D"640"></a></div>
</span>
In my example, my <b>serial port is number 2</b>. <ul>
<li>The 'Printer' is using "Serial Port 1".</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<div>
<h2>
In the guest (Virtual Machine) context</h2>
</div>
</div>
<h3>
For guests (VMs) running Windows Vista and later.</h3>
<div>
<ol>
<li>Start the VM.</li>
<li>After Windows is finished loading, run "Command Prompt" (Start+R &gt; c=
md.exe) as an Administrator.<br><ul>
<li>In Windows 10, you can right-click on the Windows logo in the taskbar (=
bottom-left) and select "Command Prompt (Admin)".</li>
</ul>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">
<a href=3D"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/YrRxmSS9_fJAgxEu0SCWteiEv1tsFN=
XvKoLzkBfAoj0D9TDqx-7yG_5sl8BT3yQxfOflj_xSf8NoXmikildo7frummkeObpQEMmuczbKE=
o2aLNLHUJhp8K9cJkF2uUZUbh84JLEC" style=3D"font-family: arial; font-size: 11=
pt; white-space: pre-wrap;" target=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"547" src=3D"ht=
tps://lh6.googleusercontent.com/YrRxmSS9_fJAgxEu0SCWteiEv1tsFNXvKoLzkBfAoj0=
D9TDqx-7yG_5sl8BT3yQxfOflj_xSf8NoXmikildo7frummkeObpQEMmuczbKEo2aLNLHUJhp8K=
9cJkF2uUZUbh84JLEC" style=3D"border: none; transform: rotate(0rad);" width=
=3D"720"></a></div>
</li>
<li>Input the following commands in this elevated prompt:
</li>
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier ne=
w&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">bcdedit /debug on</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier ne=
w&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">bcdedit /dbgsettings serial deb=
ugport:2 baudrate:115200</span>
</li>
<ul>
<li>Make sure your <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &=
quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">debugport</span>=
 argument matches your serial port number from step 7 in the "Setting up VM=
ware" section. My serial port number is 2 because my VM has a printer that =
is using serial port number 1.</li>
<li><b>Pro-tip</b>: You can add the <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeee=
e; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;"=
>/noumex</span> switch to the the <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee;=
 font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">d=
bgsettings</span> command, e.g. <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; f=
ont-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">bcd=
edit /dbgsettings serial debugport:2 baudrate:115200 /noumex</span>. This a=
voids user mode exceptions from causing the system to break into the kernel=
 debugger.</li>
</ul>
</ul>
<li>Now validate that the settings have been successfully applied:
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier ne=
w&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">bcdedit /dbgsettings</span></li=
>
<li><span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier ne=
w&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">bcdedit</span></li>
</ul>
You should see similar command prompt output to this:<br><span style=3D"fon=
t-family: &quot;arial&quot;; font-size: 11pt; vertical-align: baseline; whi=
te-space: pre-wrap;"><a href=3D"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/qJI5fj3oq=
cSmlJMoeVE_xW6DIo8knoveYGvvi7CUqIsaDz2-eZu9vwXNipDw2h9hETKZ89HnqJ3_lwKoPGi2=
z75nJuCit8Qkk0I53I4ucGxFre_396qwydLmYEphFDys8SPj3m8U" target=3D"_blank"><im=
g height=3D"558" src=3D"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/qJI5fj3oqcSmlJMoe=
VE_xW6DIo8knoveYGvvi7CUqIsaDz2-eZu9vwXNipDw2h9hETKZ89HnqJ3_lwKoPGi2z75nJuCi=
t8Qkk0I53I4ucGxFre_396qwydLmYEphFDys8SPj3m8U" style=3D"-webkit-transform: r=
otate(0.00rad); border: none; transform: rotate(0.00rad);" width=3D"727"></=
a></span></li>
<li>Finally, shutdown Windows cleanly. You can do this via the traditional =
route (the start menu) or by executing the <span style=3D"background-color:=
 #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , mono=
space;">shutdown -s -t 0</span> command in command prompt.</li>
</ol>
<h3>
For guests (VMs) running Windows XP.</h3>
</div>
<div>
<ol>
<li>Start the VM.</li>
<li><span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee;"><span style=3D"font-family: =
&quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">bcdedit</span><=
/span> does not exist on Windows XP. To enable kernel debugging, you must a=
lter the <span style=3D"font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courie=
r&quot; , monospace;">boot.ini</span> file. The easiest way to do this is b=
y clicking on Start and then Run (Start+R). Enter <span style=3D"font-famil=
y: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">C:\boot.ini<=
/span> as the argument and hit 'OK'.
<ul>
<li>You might have to change the drive letter (from <span style=3D"font-fam=
ily: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">C:\</span>=
) if your operating system is installed on a different drive.</li>
<li>This file is hidden (and considered a protected operating system file).=
 Therefore, it won't be displayed in Windows Explorer by default.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Append the string <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family=
: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">/debug /debug=
port=3DCOM2 /baudrate=3D115200</span> to the end of the first entry in the =
[operating systems] section.
<ul>
<li>Make sure your <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &=
quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;">debugport</span>=
 argument matches your serial port number from step 7 in the "Setting up VM=
ware" section. My serial port number is 2 (hence <span style=3D"background-=
color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; =
, monospace;">COM2</span>) because my VM has a printer that is using serial=
 port number 1.</li>
</ul>
<div style=3D"text-align: center;">
<a href=3D"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/YwJOVBpuo0F1y-u69h3VwAXK2unUpQ=
xIEeUalGAA0aQUdJ2wMhVP-olBg5qESKhL_HPNjfZhAwoCGrFQWF_PBJCkN9Wb8xbTfisQkCcmx=
LNNSLtvlcPTLPI59K8sTCdwmxlsu-IJ" style=3D"font-family: arial; font-size: 11=
pt; white-space: pre-wrap;" target=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"492" src=3D"ht=
tps://lh6.googleusercontent.com/YwJOVBpuo0F1y-u69h3VwAXK2unUpQxIEeUalGAA0aQ=
UdJ2wMhVP-olBg5qESKhL_HPNjfZhAwoCGrFQWF_PBJCkN9Wb8xbTfisQkCcmxLNNSLtvlcPTLP=
I59K8sTCdwmxlsu-IJ" style=3D"border: 1pt solid rgb(0, 0, 0); transform: rot=
ate(0rad);" width=3D"655"></a></div>
</li>
<li>Save the <span style=3D"font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;co=
urier&quot; , monospace;">boot.ini</span> via "File" and then "Save" from t=
he menu bar (or hit Control+S). Close the file.</li>
<li>Finally, shutdown Windows cleanly via the traditional route (the start =
menu).</li>
</ol>
<h2>
Finalizing WinDbg on your host</h2>
</div>
<div>
<ol>
<li>Open the shortcut to your WinDbg that you created in step 2 in the "Set=
ting up symbols on your host" section.</li>
<li>Click on "File" and then "Kernel Debug..." (or press Ctrl+K). Select th=
e "COM" tab and use your settings from the previous sections. If you've bee=
n following the tutorial verbatim, you can just use these settings:<br><spa=
n style=3D"font-family: &quot;arial&quot;; font-size: 11pt; vertical-align:=
 baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"><a href=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent=
.com/ruHB5CfPqoMkIpBJlfD5iinCRC1TaxzYhLXP5cZPWkJo_Ydic8cfxfhScyESeH8LUSuVtQ=
XeNgU6G27Xr6y7EdndPTSsT2wIjlPyX44lqc8io5Qin-cewHzESeOgl1e1c9VgSITd"><img he=
ight=3D"445" src=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/ruHB5CfPqoMkIpBJlfD5i=
inCRC1TaxzYhLXP5cZPWkJo_Ydic8cfxfhScyESeH8LUSuVtQXeNgU6G27Xr6y7EdndPTSsT2wI=
jlPyX44lqc8io5Qin-cewHzESeOgl1e1c9VgSITd" style=3D"border: none; transform:=
 rotate(0rad);" width=3D"720"></a></span></li>
<li>Finally, hit 'OK' and launch your Virtual Machine. WinDbg should automa=
tically establish a connection to VMware when Windows begins loading.<br><s=
pan style=3D"font-family: &quot;arial&quot;; font-size: 11pt; vertical-alig=
n: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"><a href=3D"https://lh3.googleuserconte=
nt.com/E_5xO55jj_BcF4j7WA242YT7b8RJO_cSZzh664MRad7zE6MwfX141Oe0aw7ggebEg3Ja=
doyNHz7EULh5cbN0ClQiy7xmYER3UPz52JEEByNXOBAz28UQSLaUSLRkd4MBBhqWPCbc" targe=
t=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"435" src=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/E=
_5xO55jj_BcF4j7WA242YT7b8RJO_cSZzh664MRad7zE6MwfX141Oe0aw7ggebEg3JadoyNHz7E=
ULh5cbN0ClQiy7xmYER3UPz52JEEByNXOBAz28UQSLaUSLRkd4MBBhqWPCbc" style=3D"bord=
er: none; transform: rotate(0rad);" width=3D"720"></a></span></li>
<li>Break into the debugger by pressing Ctrl+Break or by selecting "Debug" =
and then "Break" from the menu bar. At this point, the Virtual Machine will=
 be in a suspended state (e.g. Windows will stop loading).</li>
<li>Load your kernel symbols with a <span style=3D"background-color: #eeeee=
e; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace;"=
>.reload /f</span> command. Then list the loaded modules via <span style=3D=
"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;co=
urier&quot; , monospace;">lm</span>. If you're having troubles loading symb=
ols, review the "Setting up symbols on your host" section above and work th=
rough the "Troubleshooting" tips if all else fails.</li>
<li>Congratulations. At this point you've successfully set up kernel debugg=
ing using WinDbg and VMware over a virtual serial connection.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div>
<h2>
Extra special bonus stage</h2>
</div>
<h3>
Modifying the shortcut to start kernel debugging immediately</h3>
<div>
Having to manually configure WinDbg each time for kernel debugging is a rea=
l pain. Luckily, there is a better way.&nbsp;</div>
<div>
<ol>
<li>Right-click on the shortcut that you created for WinDbg. Select "Proper=
ties". In the "Shortcut" tab, you'll see a window similar to this:<br><span=
 style=3D"font-family: &quot;arial&quot;; font-size: 11pt; vertical-align: =
baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"><a href=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent.=
com/FqluK-Q1lXtOum1Rsbo5uM7gl4V7F4zQIHSAItxrnSFIjU9qqukayImdaInFndnRYADJTAo=
STl-QlzFv3w6ggd8SE5H5EqyE7RpqXHwVcm0AtBal35rJE-cHD4cMfA8i2sbuyrbm" target=
=3D"_blank"><img height=3D"533" src=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/Fq=
luK-Q1lXtOum1Rsbo5uM7gl4V7F4zQIHSAItxrnSFIjU9qqukayImdaInFndnRYADJTAoSTl-Ql=
zFv3w6ggd8SE5H5EqyE7RpqXHwVcm0AtBal35rJE-cHD4cMfA8i2sbuyrbm" style=3D"borde=
r: none; transform: rotate(0rad);" width=3D"377"></a></span></li>
<li>Append the following string to the "Target:" textbox:<br><span style=3D=
"background-color: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;co=
urier&quot; , monospace;">-k com:pipe,port=3D\\.\pipe\com_1,resets=3D0,reco=
nnect</span>
<ul>
<li>You might have to change the pipe name from <span style=3D"background-c=
olor: #eeeeee; font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; ,=
 monospace;">com_1</span> to whatever you selected in step 6 in the "Settin=
g up VMware on your host" section.</li>
<li>The final "Target:" argument should look similar to this:<br><span styl=
e=3D"font-family: &quot;courier new&quot; , &quot;courier&quot; , monospace=
;">"C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\Debuggers\x64\windbg.exe" <span =
style=3D"background-color: #eeeeee;">-y "srv*c:\symbols*https://msdl.micros=
oft.com/download/symbols" -k com:pipe,port=3D\\.\pipe\com_1,resets=3D0,reco=
nnect</span></span></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Hit 'OK' and you should be all set. Now when you run this shortcut of W=
inDbg, it will correctly configure your symbol path (without having to use =
yucky environment variables) and will automatically start kernel debugging =
the first active named pipe.</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
